e\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_main_2525844\" data-toggle=\"modal\" role=\"button\" tabindex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Sept 10, 2024</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent wide\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104arf1665702893579.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/arf1665702893579.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/arf1665702893579.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"arf1665702893579\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Configuring Java Call-In\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body taskbody\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Uniface uses the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) to support Java call-in at runtime, and the Java Developer Kit for compiling and packaging generated Java wrapper files. You need to configure Uniface so that it can locate these facilities when required, and you need to enable Java to find the Uniface Java call-in DLLs.\n </p>\n<section class=\"section context\" id=\"arf1665702893579__context_w5832ab1b5b1_w5833ab1b5_w5834ab1\">\n<div class=\"div prereq\" id=\"arf1665702893579__topic_d35939e1_d35940e1_d35941e1\">\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"arf1665702893579__p_d35942e1_d35943e1_d35944e1\">A Java Developer Kit must be installed. During\n               installation, you can choose to install the JRE provided with Uniface (OpenJDK 17),\n               or you can have Uniface use an existing JRE installation. By default, the installer\n               configures Uniface to use the <span class=\"ph filepath\">jvm.dll</span> provided by the specified\n               JRE by adding the location to the [USER_3GL] of the <span class=\"ph filepath\">usys.asn</span>\n               file.</p>\n</div>\n</section>\n<section><ol class=\"ol steps\"><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"arf1665702893579__li_d18338e1_d18339e1_d18340e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Configure Uniface for Java call-in:\n </span>\n<ol class=\"ol substeps\" type=\"a\">\n<li class=\"li substep substepexpand\" id=\"arf1665702893579__li_d18341e1_d18342e1_d18343e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Edit the Windows environment variables PATH and CLASSPATH:\n </span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<ul class=\"ul\">\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"arf1665702893579__li_d18344e1_d18345e1_d18346e1\">PATH—add the paths to the JDK <span class=\"ph filepath\">/bin</span> directory and the Uniface <span class=\"ph filepath\">common/bin</span> directory.\n </li>\n<li class=\"li\" id=\"arf1665702893579__li_d18347e1_d18348e1_d18349e1\">CLASSPATH—add the path to the\n                              <span class=\"ph filepath\">ujci30.jar</span> file in the Uniface\n                              <span class=\"ph filepath\">common/bin</span> directory. </li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n</li>\n<li class=\"li substep substepexpand\" id=\"arf1665702893579__li_d18350e1_d18351e1_d18352e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\">Ensure that the location of the <span class=\"ph filepath\">jvm.dll</span> is specified in the [USER_3GL] section of the <span class=\"ph filepath\">usys.asn</span> file.\n </span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"arf1665702893579__note_w5835ab1b5b3b1b3b3b3b1_w5836ab1b5b3b1b3b3b3_w5837ab1b5b3b1b3b3_w5838ab1b5b3b1b3_w5839ab1b5b3b1_w5840ab1b5b3_w5841ab1b5_w5842ab1\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> The JRE is also used for other Uniface functionality, so if you change this value, you may also need to perform other steps.</div>\n</div>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</li><li class=\"li step stepexpand\" id=\"arf1665702893579__li_d18353e1_d18354e1_d18355e1\">\n<span class=\"ph cmd\" id=\"arf1665702893579__p_d35945e1_d35946e1_d35947e1\">Configure the JDK to locate the Uniface call-in\n               DLLs by setting the system property uniface.bindir. For example:</span>\n<div class=\"itemgroup info\">\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">java.lang.System.setProperty(\"uniface.bindir\",\"C://Uniface 10//common//bin\");</code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<p class=\"p\">or</p>\n<div class=\"code-toolbar\"><pre class=\"pre language-plaintext\" tabindex=\"0\"><code class=\"language-plaintext\">java -Duniface.bindir=\"C://Uniface 10//common//bin\" </code></pre><div class=\"toolbar\"><div class=\"toolbar-item\"><button class=\"copy-to-clipboard-button\" data-copy-state=\"copy\" type=\"button\"><span>Copy</span></button></div></div></div>\n<div class=\"note note note_note\" id=\"arf1665702893579__note_w5843ab1b5b3b3b3b7_w5844ab1b5b3b3b3_w5845ab1b5b3b3_w5846ab1b5b3_w5847ab1b5_w5848ab1\"><span class=\"note__title\">Note:</span> For other Uniface call-in properties, you can use the\n                     <span class=\"keyword apiname\">ConfigManager</span> or\n                  <span class=\"keyword apiname\">ConfigManagerBean</span>.</div>\n</div>\n</li></ol></section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2525844\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2525844\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Configuring Java Call-In Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Sept 10, 2024 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Configuring Java Call-In Uniface uses the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) to support Java call-in at runtime, and the Java Developer Kit for compiling and packaging generated Java wrapper files. You need to configure Uniface so that it can locate these facilities when required, and you need to enable Java to find the Uniface Java call-in DLLs. A Java Developer Kit must be installed. During installation, you can choose to install the JRE provided with Uniface (OpenJDK 17), or you can have Uniface use an existing JRE installation. By default, the installer configures Uniface to use the jvm.dll provided by the specified JRE by adding the location to the [USER_3GL] of the usys.asn file. Configure Uniface for Java call-in: Edit the Windows environment variables PATH and CLASSPATH: PATH—add the paths to the JDK /bin directory and the Uniface common/bin directory. CLASSPATH—add the path to the ujci30.jar file in the Uniface common/bin directory. Ensure that the location of the jvm.dll is specified in the [USER_3GL] section of the usys.asn file. Note: The JRE is also used for other Uniface functionality, so if you change this value, you may also need to perform other steps. Configure the JDK to locate the Uniface call-in DLLs by setting the system property uniface.bindir. For example: java.lang.System.setProperty(\"uniface.bindir\",\"C://Uniface 10//common//bin\"); Copy or java -Duniface.bindir=\"C://Uniface 10//common//bin\" Copy Note: For other Uniface call-in properties, you can use the ConfigManager or ConfigManagerBean . Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}